Got it.

13
00:01:17,396 --> 00:01:18,320
Ooh.

14
00:01:18,977 --> 00:01:20,251
Come on, Gina.

15
00:01:20,463 --> 00:01:22,369
I'm not having this
conversation with you again.

16
00:01:22,370 --> 00:01:24,358
Well, I'm... I gotta go.
I'm at work.

17
00:01:24,754 --> 00:01:26,228
It is so work.

18
00:01:27,065 --> 00:01:28,789
What's up, Castle? How's it going?

19
00:01:28,880 --> 00:01:32,403
You want my advice? Never sleep
with someone you work with.

20
00:01:33,170 --> 00:01:35,485
What? What do you mean?

21
00:01:35,486 --> 00:01:37,335
Trust me. It doesn't end well.

22
00:01:37,336 --> 00:01:38,428
Who knows?

23
00:01:39,529 --> 00:01:41,067
Everyone knows.

24
00:01:41,088 --> 00:01:42,464
Everyone knows what?

25
00:01:42,465 --> 00:01:43,428
Nothing.

26
00:01:45,311 --> 00:01:46,348
On my way.

27
00:01:46,516 --> 00:01:48,307
You okay, Castle? You seem upset.

28
00:01:48,308 --> 00:01:51,036
No, no, I'm fine. Why?

29
00:01:51,332 --> 00:01:52,214
Okay.

30
00:01:54,217 --> 00:01:56,545
The murder is here at
Drake's Magic Shop?

31
00:01:56,546 --> 00:01:57,336
Yep.

32
00:01:57,337 --> 00:01:59,544
I've been coming here
since I was 13 years old.

33
00:01:59,545 --> 00:02:02,221
This place is a
paradise for boys...

34
00:02:02,257 --> 00:02:05,217
Whoopee cushions,
magic tricks, fake vomit.

35
00:02:05,218 --> 00:02:06,970
It's not just for boys, Castle.

36
00:02:06,971 --> 00:02:08,745
My grandfather was
an amateur magician,

37
00:02:08,746 --> 00:02:11,033
and I used to come here
almost every Sunday afternoon

38
00:02:11,034 --> 00:02:12,846
when I was that age, too.

39
00:02:14,058 --> 00:02:15,966
I never pegged you
for a magic fan.

40
00:02:16,234 --> 00:02:17,607
You know any good tricks?

41
00:02:18,493 --> 00:02:19,484
I do this one thing

42
00:02:19,485 --> 00:02:21,096
with ice cubes.

43
00:02:22,734 --> 00:02:24,159
According to his
water-soaked wallet,

44
00:02:24,160 --> 00:02:26,817
the victim's Zalman Drake,
the shop owner.

45
00:02:26,818 --> 00:02:30,086
His assistant, Eliza Winter,
found him in the tank

46
00:02:30,087 --> 00:02:31,776
when she opened up the
store this morning.

47
00:02:31,777 --> 00:02:33,026
Any signs of forced entry?

48
00:02:33,027 --> 00:02:35,327
No. You know, it is beyond me

49
00:02:35,328 --> 00:02:36,874
why people think
this is entertaining.

50
00:02:36,875 --> 00:02:39,201
I see a guy hanging upside
down in a water tank,

51
00:02:39,202 --> 00:02:40,809
I think, you are a fool.

52
00:02:40,810 --> 00:02:44,410
Hmm. See the milk cans and
the water torture tank,

53
00:02:44,411 --> 00:02:46,404
they were real game
changers in the magic world.

54
00:02:46,405 --> 00:02:47,866
They were the first presentation

55
00:02:47,867 --> 00:02:50,188
of real life-and-death
consequences.

56
00:02:50,189 --> 00:02:53,368
As the magician held his breath,
so did the audience.

57
00:02:53,499 --> 00:02:55,371
Well, this magician would've
had to hold his breath

58
00:02:55,372 --> 00:02:57,593
eight to ten hours if
he wanted to take a bow.

59
00:02:57,594 --> 00:03:01,087
So you're saying between 12:00 and 2:00 A.M.?
Looks that way,

60
00:03:01,088 --> 00:03:04,644
petechial hemorrhaging in
his eyes indicate drowning.

61
00:03:04,906 --> 00:03:08,152
Failed escape attempt?
Well, there's no redness around his ankles

62
00:03:08,153 --> 00:03:09,054
where he was hanging.

63
00:03:09,055 --> 00:03:11,487
Doesn't look like he
struggled to get out.

64
00:03:11,488 --> 00:03:13,370
I have a feeling he was dead
before he hit the water,

65
00:03:13,371 --> 00:03:15,466
but I won't know for sure until
I get him back to the lab.

66
00:03:15,467 --> 00:03:17,387
Maybe there's another
reason he didn't struggle.

67
00:03:18,879 --> 00:03:20,282
Suicide note.

68
00:03:20,351 --> 00:03:21,622
It says he was in
financial trouble

69
00:03:21,623 --> 00:03:23,592
and couldn't bear the thought
of losing his family's shop,

70
00:03:23,593 --> 00:03:27,460
so he was gonna kill himself.
Mr. Drake did not kill himself.

71
00:03:28,527 --> 00:03:30,707
How do you know?
I just know.

72
00:03:30,804 --> 00:03:33,487
- Is it true, though? Was he gonna lose
his shop? - No.

73
00:03:33,540 --> 00:03:36,555
I mean, yes, but two
weeks ago, he told me

74
00:03:36,556 --> 00:03:37,443
that everything was fine,

75
00:03:37,444 --> 00:03:39,946
that he had worked it all out.
Any idea how?

76
00:03:39,947 --> 00:03:42,363
Was there a windfall
or an investor?

77
00:03:42,364 --> 00:03:43,952
He didn't say.

78
00:03:43,953 --> 00:03:44,518
Would he have been able

79
00:03:44,519 --> 00:03:47,741
to place himself in that tank?
Absolutely.

80
00:03:47,864 --> 00:03:50,470
But he wouldn't have.
Not Zalman.

81
00:03:50,471 --> 00:03:52,929
He loved and respected
magic too much.

82
00:03:54,658 --> 00:03:56,731
Esposito, there's
no signature here.

83
00:03:58,173 --> 00:04:00,404
I'll have C.S.U. run it for prints.
Have them run the tank

84
00:04:00,405 --> 00:04:02,811
and the entries and exits as well.
Okay.

85
00:04:03,570 --> 00:04:04,798
When was the last
time you saw him?

86
00:04:04,799 --> 00:04:07,741
Yesterday morning.
He left right after lunch,

87
00:04:07,742 --> 00:04:09,411
and he was gone the
rest of the day.

88
00:04:09,412 --> 00:04:13,092
Did he say where he was going?
Was it normal for him

89
00:04:13,093 --> 00:04:14,641
to leave the shop in
the middle of the day?

90
00:04:14,642 --> 00:04:17,238
Yeah. He would do that sometimes.

91
00:04:17,243 --> 00:04:19,178
Did you notice any
changes in his behavior

92
00:04:19,179 --> 00:04:21,929
or anything unusual
going on in his life?

93
00:04:21,930 --> 00:04:25,458
This past month,
he was gone m-more often.

94
00:04:25,459 --> 00:04:28,608
All he'd say was that he
was working on something.

95
00:04:29,084 --> 00:04:32,343
But he looked a little tired,
like he hadn't been sleeping.

96
00:04:32,508 --> 00:04:34,384
Can you think of any
reason for the change?

97
00:04:34,385 --> 00:04:38,272
Yes. Last month,
right before all this started,

98
00:04:38,273 --> 00:04:40,901
a guy came into the shop
and attacked Mr. Drake.

99
00:04:40,902 --> 00:04:43,214
He pushed him right
through a display case.

100
00:04:43,215 --> 00:04:44,653
He said he better watch his back,

101
00:04:44,654 --> 00:04:47,114
and he was gonna sue him
for all he was worth.

102
00:04:49,792 --> 00:04:51,419
Thank you. I will hold.

103
00:04:51,550 --> 00:04:53,206
So court records show that

104
00:04:53,207 --> 00:04:56,229
a lawsuit was filed against
Zalman Drake a month ago.

105
00:04:56,230 --> 00:04:57,938
They're pulling it up now.
Hey.

106
00:04:57,939 --> 00:04:59,969
Hey. We canvassed the area
around the magic shop.

107
00:04:59,970 --> 00:05:02,013
One of the neighbors said
she saw an old white van

108
00:05:02,014 --> 00:05:03,633
pull up to the shop
around midnight

109
00:05:03,634 --> 00:05:06,149
and then heard the gate roll up.
Okay, you guys look into that,

110
00:05:06,150 --> 00:05:08,151
and let's find out where
Zalman was disappearing to.

111
00:05:08,152 --> 00:05:09,132
I'd like to know what he was doing

112
00:05:09,133 --> 00:05:11,066
all the way up until the
moment that he died.

113
00:05:11,071 --> 00:05:12,091
What about his next of kin?

114
00:05:12,092 --> 00:05:14,172
Only surviving relative's
a brother in Poughkeepsie.

115
00:05:14,173 --> 00:05:16,572
We haven't reached him yet.
All right, thank you, guys.

116
00:05:17,072 --> 00:05:18,731
Poughkeepsie?
Hey.

117
00:05:19,558 --> 00:05:22,155
X-ray specs.
Got 'em at the magic shop.

118
00:05:23,140 --> 00:05:24,954
I can see you naked.

119
00:05:25,077 --> 00:05:26,342
Really?
Mm.

120
00:05:26,560 --> 00:05:28,079
How do you like my navel ring?

121
00:05:28,847 --> 00:05:30,614
Looks like somebody has a secret.

122
00:05:30,615 --> 00:05:34,060
A secret? Uh, what secret?

123
00:05:34,134 --> 00:05:36,206
I can understand a guy
not wanting to share.

124
00:05:36,207 --> 00:05:38,307
I mean, some things are personal.

125
00:05:39,156 --> 00:05:40,515
How did you find out?

126
00:05:40,896 --> 00:05:42,292
Dude, everybody knows.

127
00:05:42,719 --> 00:05:44,107
It's all over "page six."

128
00:05:49,391 --> 00:05:50,406
"Looks like an unhappy ending

129
00:05:50,407 --> 00:05:51,881
for the publisher and
the mystery writer."

130
00:05:51,882 --> 00:05:52,921
Apparently,

131
00:05:52,922 --> 00:05:57,436
he and ex-wife/girlfriend/
publisher Gina

132
00:05:57,437 --> 00:06:00,283
had some words...
loud words... at Le Cirque,

133
00:06:00,284 --> 00:06:01,676
and she stormed off.

134
00:06:01,677 --> 00:06:03,792
That's what he was talking
about this morning.

135
00:06:03,793 --> 00:06:05,295
What I don't understand
is why he would try

136
00:06:05,296 --> 00:06:07,948
to hide it from us.
I mean, we're like family.

137
00:06:07,949 --> 00:06:10,074
Maybe he's afraid of
what we might think.

138
00:06:11,949 --> 00:06:15,142
So it turns out a lawsuit was
filed against Zalman Drake

139
00:06:15,143 --> 00:06:17,652
by a Jerome Aspenall.

140
00:06:17,653 --> 00:06:19,046
And get this...

141
00:06:19,057 --> 00:06:21,058
The judge threw it out yesterday.

142
00:06:21,059 --> 00:06:24,454
Maybe Jerome decided to take
justice into his own hands.

143
00:06:24,872 --> 00:06:26,264
What was he suing him for?

144
00:06:26,265 --> 00:06:28,684
Zalman Drake?
I was suing him for slander,

145
00:06:28,685 --> 00:06:30,718
defamation of character,
ruining my life.

146
00:06:30,719 --> 00:06:33,930
And how did Zalman do that, Jerome?
He read my friggin' mind,

147
00:06:33,931 --> 00:06:36,669
in front of, like, 300 people.
During a magic performance?

148
00:06:36,670 --> 00:06:38,006
Yeah. It was like
this mind reading,

149
00:06:38,007 --> 00:06:40,687
card tricks, levitation,
at this chichi charity ball.

150
00:06:40,688 --> 00:06:41,708
My in-laws won a table,

151
00:06:41,709 --> 00:06:43,496
and I figured, free food,
some entertainment,

152
00:06:43,497 --> 00:06:45,774
maybe later, I get lucky.
Turns out not so lucky.

153
00:06:45,775 --> 00:06:47,376
Could you elaborate on that?
Yeah,

154
00:06:47,377 --> 00:06:49,584
this magician, Zalman Drake,
gets onstage,

155
00:06:49,585 --> 00:06:51,455
makes this rich dude
disappear and reappear,

156
00:06:51,456 --> 00:06:52,589
and I'm like, "Oh, that's cool."

157
00:06:52,590 --> 00:06:55,168
Then he asks for volunteers.
My wife raises my hand

158
00:06:55,169 --> 00:06:57,496
and says "Go up there, it'll be fun,"
so I do. Drake says,

159
00:06:57,497 --> 00:07:00,518
"Stand across from me and
think good thoughts," so I do.

160
00:07:00,519 --> 00:07:02,023
He looks at me, concentrates,

161
00:07:02,024 --> 00:07:04,584
puts his fingers on my forehead,
and he goes, "You're thinking

162
00:07:04,585 --> 00:07:08,172
of Rita and your trip to Atlantic
city last weekend." Were you?

163
00:07:08,353 --> 00:07:10,373
Yeah, but I was trying not to,

164
00:07:10,401 --> 00:07:12,428
'cause here's the kicker...
Your wife's name isn't Rita.

165
00:07:12,429 --> 00:07:13,700
Right.
Mm.

166
00:07:13,701 --> 00:07:16,534
So now I'm living in a
motel in Long Island City,

167
00:07:16,535 --> 00:07:19,230
my father-in-law fired me,
and Rita won't even talk to me

168
00:07:19,231 --> 00:07:20,662
'cause my wife found her
number and called her.

169
00:07:20,663 --> 00:07:22,806
Where were you last night
between 12:00 and 2:00?

170
00:07:24,167 --> 00:07:25,103
Why is she asking me that?

171
00:07:25,104 --> 00:07:28,105
Well, she wants to know if you have an alibi.
For what?

172
00:07:28,106 --> 00:07:31,051
Zalman Drake was
murdered last night.

173
00:07:33,638 --> 00:07:35,234
Justice is served.

174
00:07:37,375 --> 00:07:40,389
When he read your mind,
did it take him very long?

175
00:07:40,390 --> 00:07:43,876
No, he... No. No.
Didn't think so.

176
00:07:43,877 --> 00:07:46,675
Jerome, we have a witness who
says you went to his shop,

177
00:07:46,676 --> 00:07:48,596
attacked, and
threatened Zalman Drake.

178
00:07:48,597 --> 00:07:50,507
When they dropped your
lawsuit yesterday,

179
00:07:50,508 --> 00:07:52,986
did you decide to take the
law into your own hands?

180
00:07:52,987 --> 00:07:55,150
Did you go to the magic
shop and murder Zalman?

181
00:07:55,151 --> 00:07:56,468
No, I didn't go
anywhere last night

182
00:07:56,469 --> 00:07:58,563
except for O'Lannahan's
at 57th and Seventh,

183
00:07:58,564 --> 00:08:00,883
because thanks to Zalman Drake,
I no longer have a wife

184
00:08:00,884 --> 00:08:03,210
or a mistress to go home to.

185
00:08:04,085 --> 00:08:05,341
Wonder how Zalman did it.

186
00:08:05,342 --> 00:08:06,983
He must have lifted something
from Jerome's pocket

187
00:08:06,984 --> 00:08:09,143
with a receipt from
his weekend of sin.

188
00:08:09,144 --> 00:08:10,106
Like this.

189
00:08:11,786 --> 00:08:14,105
You had your hand in my pocket,
and I didn't even feel it?

190
00:08:14,106 --> 00:08:15,396
Do it again.

191
00:08:26,695 --> 00:08:27,594
What?

192
00:08:28,200 --> 00:08:29,266
Hey, Ryan.

193
00:08:30,022 --> 00:08:32,998
Any luck narrowing down
Zalman's whereabouts yesterday?

194
00:08:32,999 --> 00:08:34,337
Uh, not yet,

195
00:08:34,338 --> 00:08:36,907
but I did check into Jerome's
whereabouts last night.

196
00:08:36,908 --> 00:08:39,202
The barkeep at O'Lannahan's
said he was there till closing.

197
00:08:39,203 --> 00:08:40,486
He called him a cab. So the only

198
00:08:40,487 --> 00:08:42,461
thing he killed last night
were his brain cells.

199
00:08:42,462 --> 00:08:45,469
And a forensic sweep of the
water tank came up negative

200
00:08:45,470 --> 00:08:48,102
for any prints on the operating
apparatus other than Zalman's.

201
00:08:48,103 --> 00:08:50,692
So either he committed suicide...
Or the killer wore gloves.

202
00:08:50,693 --> 00:08:52,695
Not the whole time.
According to the lab,

203
00:08:52,696 --> 00:08:54,893
there were fingerprints all
over that suicide note,

204
00:08:54,894 --> 00:08:56,668
and they weren't
Zalman's or Jerome's.

205
00:08:56,669 --> 00:08:59,996
Did you get a match? Yeah,
to a Charles "Chuck" Russell.

206
00:08:59,997 --> 00:09:01,290
A low-life street magician

207
00:09:01,291 --> 00:09:02,780
with three arrests
and two convictions...

208
00:09:02,781 --> 00:09:04,017
one for arson and another on

209
00:09:04,018 --> 00:09:06,676
an explosives charge.
Did he know our victim?

210
00:09:06,677 --> 00:09:08,950
Yeah, apparently Zalman
is some big muckety-muck

211
00:09:08,951 --> 00:09:10,247
with the American Magicians Guild.

212
00:09:10,248 --> 00:09:12,713
They have a code of professional conduct,
and Chuck broke it.

213
00:09:12,714 --> 00:09:14,958
He was reckless with
pyrotechnics in his act,

214
00:09:14,959 --> 00:09:17,519
injured his assistant,
so Zalman had him kicked out.

215
00:09:17,520 --> 00:09:20,829
He hasn't been able to book a gig since.
Where can we find him?

216
00:09:20,830 --> 00:09:22,750
So I have Brenda's watch here.

217
00:09:22,751 --> 00:09:24,374
She wants me to make
her husband disappear.

218
00:09:24,375 --> 00:09:26,228
That's a felony. I can't do that.

219
00:09:26,229 --> 00:09:29,709
But I can make the
watch disappear.

220
00:09:29,710 --> 00:09:30,719
Give it up. That was
incredible, really.

221
00:09:32,474 --> 00:09:33,744
Thank you, Brenda.

222
00:09:34,939 --> 00:09:37,055
Aw. $1.

223
00:09:38,467 --> 00:09:41,455
I'll dine on raman and tap
water tonight and think of you.

224
00:09:41,875 --> 00:09:42,846
What about you?
You got a little something

225
00:09:42,847 --> 00:09:45,297
for the United Magicians College fund?

226
00:09:45,298 --> 00:09:46,904
As a matter of fact, I do.

227
00:09:47,027 --> 00:09:49,256
We need to talk to you
about Zalman Drake.

228
00:09:49,884 --> 00:09:51,313
Abracadabra.

229
00:10:06,210 --> 00:10:08,457
Alakazam, jackass.

230
00:10:22,408 --> 00:10:23,638
Why am I here?

231
00:10:24,238 --> 00:10:27,806
You recognize this?
That's a baggie and that's a letter.

232
00:10:27,807 --> 00:10:28,803
Next.

233
00:10:28,987 --> 00:10:31,663
Careful, Chucky.
Next could be a murder charge.

234
00:10:31,664 --> 00:10:33,951
Your fingerprints are on it.
So?

235
00:10:33,952 --> 00:10:36,629
So I find it strange that
someone else's fingerprints

236
00:10:36,630 --> 00:10:38,918
are on another guy's suicide note.

237
00:10:38,919 --> 00:10:42,324
What are you talking about?
Your old friend Zalman Drake.

238
00:10:42,776 --> 00:10:43,787
Zalman?

239
00:10:46,435 --> 00:10:47,709
Yeah, that's him.

240
00:10:48,146 --> 00:10:49,328
He killed himself?

241
00:10:49,329 --> 00:10:51,434
Man.
We found him drowned

242
00:10:51,435 --> 00:10:53,723
in the water torture
trick in his shop.

243
00:10:53,724 --> 00:10:55,339
You must have thought
you were pretty clever,

244
00:10:55,340 --> 00:10:57,306
staging it to look
like a botched escape.

245
00:10:57,307 --> 00:11:00,519
I didn't stage anything.
I had nothing to do with it.

246
00:11:00,520 --> 00:11:03,140
Well, then maybe you can
explain your prints on that.

247
00:11:08,390 --> 00:11:09,266
All right.

248
00:11:10,134 --> 00:11:13,939
No, wait. Okay, listen,
I-I-I gave him this note.

249
00:11:13,940 --> 00:11:15,828
You gave him a suicide note?

250
00:11:15,829 --> 00:11:16,587
Not that note.

251
00:11:16,588 --> 00:11:19,345
The other note on the paper.
The one you can't see.

252
00:11:21,756 --> 00:11:23,407
Hold it under a black light.

253
00:11:25,710 --> 00:11:28,296
It's an invoice for
services rendered.

254
00:11:28,297 --> 00:11:29,859
What kind of services?

255
00:11:29,860 --> 00:11:31,599
He wanted me to get him something,

256
00:11:32,116 --> 00:11:33,360
something illegal.

257
00:11:36,395 --> 00:11:38,591
C4 explosives?

258
00:11:38,592 --> 00:11:39,860
Ironic, right?

259
00:11:40,335 --> 00:11:41,670
He wants explosives from me

260
00:11:41,671 --> 00:11:43,477
when that's what he
got me booted for.

261
00:11:43,478 --> 00:11:45,748
But he promised to get me
reinstated in the Guild,

262
00:11:45,749 --> 00:11:50,257
and I wanted to work.
Whoever wrote this note

263
00:11:50,258 --> 00:11:52,299
probably thought they took
a blank piece of paper.

264
00:11:52,300 --> 00:11:54,051
Whoever being not me.

265
00:11:54,052 --> 00:11:58,241
You provided him with enough C4
to blow up half a city block.

266
00:11:58,242 --> 00:12:00,591
What was it for?
Maybe it was for a magic trick.

267
00:12:00,592 --> 00:12:01,506
Come on.

268
00:12:01,507 --> 00:12:03,768
Nah, listen, Zalman
didn't just run the shop

269
00:12:03,769 --> 00:12:05,509
and do corporate gigs.

270
00:12:05,519 --> 00:12:08,341
He was also this
genius trick designer.

271
00:12:08,642 --> 00:12:09,935
Rumor has it, he was creating

272
00:12:09,936 --> 00:12:12,899
cutting-edge illusions for
the hottest guy out there.

273
00:12:13,143 --> 00:12:15,499
And who is the hottest
guy out there?

274
00:12:15,734 --> 00:12:18,517
Tobias Strange?
He's the Johnny Depp of magic.

275
00:12:18,518 --> 00:12:20,727
I saw him in Vegas.
He made a Ferrari disappear.

276
00:12:20,728 --> 00:12:22,247
Why would anybody want to do that?
Yeah,

277
00:12:22,248 --> 00:12:24,341
he's in town. I saw him
perform a couple of weeks ago.

278
00:12:24,342 --> 00:12:26,445
Awesome, awesome show.

279
00:12:26,446 --> 00:12:27,795
Yeah, we loved it.

280
00:12:27,796 --> 00:12:28,753
We?

281
00:12:29,941 --> 00:12:30,959
Yeah.

282
00:12:31,325 --> 00:12:32,522
Me and my buddy.

283
00:12:32,966 --> 00:12:35,927
Ray.
You have a buddy named Ray

284
00:12:35,928 --> 00:12:37,404
who you went with to a magic show?

285
00:12:37,405 --> 00:12:39,726
Yeah. What about it?
Okay, guys,

286
00:12:39,727 --> 00:12:41,950
hold Chuck on an explosives
trafficking charge,

287
00:12:41,951 --> 00:12:44,512
and let's see if this "Johnny
Depp of magic" knows what his

288
00:12:44,513 --> 00:12:47,978
trick designer was really into
and why it required so much C4.

289
00:12:51,881 --> 00:12:52,774
Voilã .

290
00:12:55,577 --> 00:12:56,631
Pull it tight.

291
00:12:56,752 --> 00:12:58,080
All the way.

292
00:12:58,081 --> 00:12:59,589
Make sure it's locked.

293
00:13:00,343 --> 00:13:02,474
Okay, guys, 30 seconds,

294
00:13:02,799 --> 00:13:04,715
starting now.

295
00:13:09,318 --> 00:13:10,326
Excuse me.

296
00:13:12,511 --> 00:13:13,396
Oh, my God!

297
00:13:13,397 --> 00:13:14,651
Oh! Get it open!

298
00:13:17,716 --> 00:13:21,114
Where is he?
Hey, this is a private rehearsal.

299
00:13:21,115 --> 00:13:22,642
Who the hell let them in here?!

300
00:13:22,643 --> 00:13:24,366
All-access pass.

301
00:13:25,504 --> 00:13:26,574
Zalman has been the heart

302
00:13:26,575 --> 00:13:28,210
of the New York magic community

303
00:13:28,211 --> 00:13:30,453
since he inherited the
shop from his dad.

304
00:13:30,744 --> 00:13:34,214
It's a huge loss. I understand
that he worked for you.

305
00:13:34,415 --> 00:13:36,740
He used to.
We parted ways last month.

306
00:13:36,741 --> 00:13:38,810
Why?
I heard from one of my vendors

307
00:13:38,811 --> 00:13:41,026
that he might be working
for someone else,

308
00:13:41,027 --> 00:13:44,147
so I confronted him.
Turns out, he was poached.

309
00:13:44,148 --> 00:13:46,096
Do you know by whom?
He didn't say.

310
00:13:46,097 --> 00:13:47,182
Look, Zalman had been

311
00:13:47,183 --> 00:13:50,753
my exclusive designer and
engineer for 15 years.

312
00:13:50,870 --> 00:13:53,536
He created some of my
most famous tricks.

313
00:13:53,605 --> 00:13:55,322
If he had any stage presence,

314
00:13:55,323 --> 00:13:58,001
he would've been a
world-class magician himself.

315
00:13:58,076 --> 00:13:59,031
Well, it must have
been very upsetting

316
00:13:59,032 --> 00:14:01,271
to have him leave
after all those years.

317
00:14:02,022 --> 00:14:04,542
Didn't that put some of
your trade secrets at risk?

318
00:14:04,543 --> 00:14:06,969
A thinly veiled accusation,
Mr. Castle.

319
00:14:06,970 --> 00:14:08,610
Of course I was upset.

320
00:14:08,798 --> 00:14:10,742
But I never doubted
his discretion.

321
00:14:10,743 --> 00:14:12,262
Mr. Strange,
did any of your illusions

322
00:14:12,263 --> 00:14:15,512
require the use of an explosive?
The term "smoke and mirrors"

323
00:14:15,513 --> 00:14:17,968
isn't metaphoric in our
business, detective.

324
00:14:17,969 --> 00:14:20,752
Much of misdirection depends
on flashes of light.

325
00:14:20,753 --> 00:14:22,094
What about C4?

326
00:14:22,185 --> 00:14:24,817
The key to making
something look dangerous

327
00:14:24,818 --> 00:14:27,053
is to have complete
control over the outcome.

328
00:14:27,054 --> 00:14:31,017
C4 is too volatile,
unpredictable. It kills.

329
00:14:31,018 --> 00:14:33,008
Any idea what Zalman
would be using it for?

330
00:14:33,009 --> 00:14:34,998
Nothing magical, I assure you.

331
00:14:35,689 --> 00:14:37,328
Have you checked his workshop?

332
00:14:37,329 --> 00:14:40,478
Uh, we haven't come
across a workshop.

333
00:14:40,521 --> 00:14:42,461
It's probably where he'd been
disappearing to every day.

334
00:14:42,462 --> 00:14:44,003
Do you know where it is?
Ah,

335
00:14:44,004 --> 00:14:46,012
you know how magicians
are about secrets.

336
00:14:46,013 --> 00:14:48,094
But whatever he was working on,

337
00:14:48,211 --> 00:14:49,881
you would probably find there.

338
00:14:50,141 --> 00:14:51,356
It's an age-old story...

339
00:14:51,357 --> 00:14:54,939
magician at the top of his game,
angry that his trick designer

340
00:14:54,940 --> 00:14:56,694
has jumped ship for
the competition,

341
00:14:56,695 --> 00:14:57,999
kills him instead of

342
00:14:58,000 --> 00:15:00,272
letting his trade secrets
fall into enemy hands.

343
00:15:00,273 --> 00:15:02,984
It's magic, Castle,
not the Cold War.

344
00:15:02,985 --> 00:15:04,773
Well, if it's not the Cold War,

345
00:15:04,774 --> 00:15:05,348
why does Zalman need

346
00:15:05,349 --> 00:15:07,703
military-grade explosives?
I don't know. Hell.

347
00:15:07,704 --> 00:15:09,569
We don't even know if
it really was murder.

348
00:15:09,570 --> 00:15:12,317
For all we know, it could've
actually been a suicide.

349
00:15:13,833 --> 00:15:17,431
It's Lanie. Let me guess.
It wasn't a suicide.

350
00:15:18,920 --> 00:15:19,862
Beckett.

351
00:15:23,292 --> 00:15:25,665
It took you two long enough.
Where were you, Europe?

352
00:15:25,666 --> 00:15:28,209
Traffic. Girl,
you coulda used the gum ball.

353
00:15:28,210 --> 00:15:31,119
Dressed to the nines,
in a big hurry.

354
00:15:31,313 --> 00:15:33,969
So... where are you going
and who's the lucky victim?

355
00:15:33,970 --> 00:15:35,488
I'll tell you what, Castle,

356
00:15:35,489 --> 00:15:38,192
you tell me what's going
on between you and Gina,

357
00:15:38,193 --> 00:15:39,880
and I'll tell you where
I'm going tonight.

358
00:15:39,881 --> 00:15:41,459
What are you talking about?

359
00:15:41,460 --> 00:15:43,763
He and his girlfriend had
a big fight at Le Cirque.

360
00:15:43,764 --> 00:15:46,003
It was in the paper.
Can we talk about the victim, please?

361
00:15:46,004 --> 00:15:46,985
Okay.

362
00:15:48,213 --> 00:15:49,912
No water in the lungs.

363
00:15:50,292 --> 00:15:51,143
He wasn't drowned?

364
00:15:51,144 --> 00:15:52,425
Nope, but he was asphyxiated,

365
00:15:52,426 --> 00:15:54,861
which sometimes
presents the same way.

366
00:15:56,493 --> 00:16:00,138
Bruising. Like someone held their
hand over his nose and mouth.

367
00:16:00,139 --> 00:16:02,289
He was murdered before
he was put into the tank.

368
00:16:02,290 --> 00:16:03,969
And then his killer
took what he thought

369
00:16:03,970 --> 00:16:06,259
was a blank piece of paper and
typed out the suicide note.

370
00:16:06,260 --> 00:16:07,690
But why kill him that way?

371
00:16:07,691 --> 00:16:09,707
I mean, why make it look like a suicide?
Cover up the murder.

372
00:16:09,708 --> 00:16:13,055
The murder, or something bigger

373
00:16:13,056 --> 00:16:15,043
involving explosives?

374
00:16:16,814 --> 00:16:18,579
We gotta find that workshop.

375
00:16:24,749 --> 00:16:27,931
You are the picture of a
civilized evening at home.

376
00:16:27,932 --> 00:16:29,835
And you are a caveman.

377
00:16:29,836 --> 00:16:31,302
Darling, we are your family.

378
00:16:31,303 --> 00:16:33,324
Why didn't you tell us about this?

379
00:16:33,325 --> 00:16:36,075
Have you spoken to her,
you know, since your P.D.A.?

380
00:16:36,076 --> 00:16:37,947
My... public display of anger.

381
00:16:37,948 --> 00:16:40,645
It says you were fighting, dad.
What about?

382
00:16:40,646 --> 00:16:43,620
Well, if you must know... yes.

383
00:16:43,621 --> 00:16:47,010
We were fighting about how
much we've been fighting.

384
00:16:47,638 --> 00:16:48,804
If you don't mind, I'd really like

385
00:16:48,805 --> 00:16:52,075
to change the subject.

386
00:16:52,400 --> 00:16:54,170
What am I, 6?

387
00:16:54,410 --> 00:16:57,508
At least pull out a $20.
Wow.

388
00:17:00,175 --> 00:17:02,770
Hey, I was thinking...
Come on, Castle. Keep up.

389
00:17:03,166 --> 00:17:05,439
Where are we going?
Zalman's workshop.

390
00:17:05,440 --> 00:17:06,967
You found it? How?

391
00:17:06,968 --> 00:17:09,838
In his soggy wallet
was a soggy metrocard.

392
00:17:09,839 --> 00:17:12,225
Ryan ran it through the
automated fare database.

393
00:17:12,226 --> 00:17:15,435
He was traveling from a subway
stop near his magic shop

394
00:17:15,436 --> 00:17:17,251
to the last stop out in the Bronx.

395
00:17:17,252 --> 00:17:18,468
So we're canvassing
the neighborhood.

396
00:17:18,469 --> 00:17:20,628
Do we need vests?
No, no vests.

397
00:17:20,629 --> 00:17:22,440
Remember that power outage
a couple of weeks ago,

398
00:17:22,441 --> 00:17:23,502
shut down the subway?
Yes.

399
00:17:23,503 --> 00:17:25,469
Well, I looked into
Zalman's financials.

400
00:17:25,470 --> 00:17:27,990
He hired a town car that
day with his credit card,

401
00:17:27,991 --> 00:17:30,914
and we now have his address.

402
00:17:41,167 --> 00:17:42,766
You sure this is the place?

403
00:17:42,767 --> 00:17:44,459
This is where they
dropped him off.

404
00:17:44,614 --> 00:17:47,779
Well, it looks abandoned,
bricked up.

405
00:17:48,334 --> 00:17:49,215
Look, look, look.

406
00:17:49,216 --> 00:17:50,229
Footprints.

407
00:17:50,358 --> 00:17:52,140
Yes, to nowhere.

408
00:17:53,024 --> 00:17:55,625
That's what he wanted us to think.

409
00:18:00,052 --> 00:18:01,741
Open Sesame.

410
00:18:10,113 --> 00:18:12,297
Zalman's fortress of solitude.

411
00:18:19,616 --> 00:18:20,957
Wow, Castle.

412
00:18:21,496 --> 00:18:23,351
My grandfather would've
loved this place.

413
00:18:23,352 --> 00:18:25,324
Look, he has a guillotine...

414
00:18:27,658 --> 00:18:29,789
And an iron maiden.

415
00:18:29,819 --> 00:18:32,835
He even had a zig zag box.

416
00:18:33,791 --> 00:18:36,291
You know, you would've
liked my grandfather.

417
00:18:37,319 --> 00:18:39,873
In fact, you remind
me of him a little.

418
00:18:40,725 --> 00:18:42,255
I'm flattered.
Hmm.

419
00:18:47,609 --> 00:18:48,378
Wheelchair tracks?

420
00:18:48,379 --> 00:18:50,670
Yeah, and they look fairly fresh.

421
00:18:51,193 --> 00:18:52,572
Maybe he had a visitor.

422
00:18:52,573 --> 00:18:53,488
Mm-hmm.

423
00:18:55,699 --> 00:18:56,733
They look recent.

424
00:18:57,835 --> 00:19:00,381
These papers are dated
the day he was killed.

425
00:19:01,025 --> 00:19:03,719
I'm gonna have to get C.S.U.
to sweep this whole place.

426
00:19:06,969 --> 00:19:09,069
Is this an accident or art?

427
00:19:13,986 --> 00:19:15,646
Castle, take a look at this.

428
00:19:17,474 --> 00:19:18,892
The pages are ripped,

429
00:19:18,893 --> 00:19:21,514
like he didn't want anyone to
know what he was working on.

430
00:19:25,548 --> 00:19:26,579
Zalman?

431
00:19:28,260 --> 00:19:29,496
Who the hell are you?

432
00:19:29,768 --> 00:19:31,696
Best trick ever.

433
00:19:40,655 --> 00:19:43,395
NYPD. Keep your hands
where I can see them.

434
00:19:45,741 --> 00:19:46,278
Whoa, whoa, whoa.

435
00:19:46,279 --> 00:19:48,372
What... what's going on?
What are you doing here?

436
00:19:49,342 --> 00:19:49,970
Zalman?

437
00:19:49,971 --> 00:19:53,607
Edmund. Edmund Drake.
His brother from Poughkeepsie?

438
00:19:53,608 --> 00:19:55,300
You're a twin.
Yeah.

439
00:19:57,256 --> 00:19:59,940
Can I put my hands down?
Uh, yeah.

440
00:20:00,713 --> 00:20:02,797
Why were you hiding
in the iron maiden?

441
00:20:03,459 --> 00:20:04,848
It's the entrance
from the other room.

442
00:20:04,849 --> 00:20:07,454
I'm detective Beckett.
We're here about your brother.

443
00:20:07,537 --> 00:20:10,236
So am I.
Where is he?

444
00:20:10,298 --> 00:20:11,429
You don't know?

445
00:20:12,353 --> 00:20:14,431
Mr. Drake, I'm sorry to tell you,

446
00:20:14,432 --> 00:20:16,165
but your brother is dead.

447
00:20:21,425 --> 00:20:22,621
Are you kidding me?

448
00:20:22,801 --> 00:20:25,879
He has an identical
twin who wears glasses.

449
00:20:25,880 --> 00:20:29,049
That's the worst disguise since
Clark Kent, and you believe him?

450
00:20:29,050 --> 00:20:32,224
I have no reason not to.
Look at him. He's devastated.

451
00:20:32,225 --> 00:20:34,950
It's an act. Don't you
ever go to movies?

452
00:20:35,306 --> 00:20:36,241
It's...

453
00:20:37,049 --> 00:20:38,740
It's probably Edmund who's dead,

454
00:20:38,741 --> 00:20:40,123
and that dweeb in the
next room is Zalman.

455
00:20:40,124 --> 00:20:43,257
I bet he killed his brother
to take over his life.

456
00:20:43,756 --> 00:20:46,240
As an accountant in Poughkeepsie?

457
00:20:47,005 --> 00:20:47,985
Well, I...

458
00:20:50,482 --> 00:20:52,123
I knew something was wrong

459
00:20:52,124 --> 00:20:54,215
when he called me a
couple of days ago.

460
00:20:54,216 --> 00:20:55,711
What did he call about?

461
00:20:56,627 --> 00:20:57,541
Money.

462
00:20:58,057 --> 00:20:59,951
He said someone was paying
him a half a million dollars,

463
00:20:59,952 --> 00:21:03,213
and he needed my help to hide it.
Hide it how?

464
00:21:03,214 --> 00:21:04,781
To make sure that the
government never found out

465
00:21:04,782 --> 00:21:06,066
where it came from.

466
00:21:06,559 --> 00:21:07,599
The way he was talking,
it sounded like

467
00:21:07,600 --> 00:21:09,736
he'd gotten involved
in something illegal.

468
00:21:09,737 --> 00:21:12,128
And what were you doing
at his warehouse?

469
00:21:12,129 --> 00:21:14,137
Well, I just had this
feeling yesterday

470
00:21:14,160 --> 00:21:15,783
that something was terribly wrong,

471
00:21:16,176 --> 00:21:18,389
and when I tried to reach him,
I couldn't.

472
00:21:18,665 --> 00:21:21,120
I drove down to the city.
I think it was the twin thing.

473
00:21:21,121 --> 00:21:24,811
You know, all our lives,
we've had this connection.

474
00:21:24,812 --> 00:21:27,024
Yeah, of course.
The twin thing.

475
00:21:27,413 --> 00:21:29,064
Tell me, Mr. Drake,

476
00:21:29,397 --> 00:21:30,879
given your legacy,

477
00:21:31,252 --> 00:21:33,808
why didn't you ever get into
the family business, too?

478
00:21:33,951 --> 00:21:37,226
No, I didn't have the passion...
Or the skill.

479
00:21:37,718 --> 00:21:39,219
Zalman and I, we, uh,

480
00:21:39,935 --> 00:21:42,955
we did have an act
together as kids.

481
00:21:49,444 --> 00:21:51,238
He would disappear up on stage,

482
00:21:51,239 --> 00:21:54,485
and then... then I would appear
in the back of the audience.

483
00:21:54,797 --> 00:21:55,694
I guess it was only amazing

484
00:21:55,695 --> 00:21:58,261
to people who didn't
know we were twins.

485
00:21:58,262 --> 00:22:00,483
Well, you're being modest.

486
00:22:00,759 --> 00:22:02,587
I'm sure you fooled
a lot of people.

487
00:22:03,518 --> 00:22:06,867
Mr. Drake, the activities that
your brother was involved in,

488
00:22:06,868 --> 00:22:09,124
if you looked through
his things, do you think

489
00:22:09,125 --> 00:22:11,480
that you would be able to
determine what he was doing?

490
00:22:11,481 --> 00:22:12,871
Zalman was a brilliant engineer,

491
00:22:12,872 --> 00:22:16,750
and, uh, I'm afraid my brain
just doesn't work that way.

492
00:22:16,871 --> 00:22:18,598
He was someone special, you know?

493
00:22:19,086 --> 00:22:20,212
Light up a room.

494
00:22:21,384 --> 00:22:23,046
Look, detective, I don't
know what he got mixed up in.

495
00:22:23,047 --> 00:22:26,199
But I just know,
he didn't deserve to die.

496
00:22:30,503 --> 00:22:32,231
I can't believe you're letting
him just walk out of here.

497
00:22:32,232 --> 00:22:34,222
If this was a movie...
It's not a movie,

498
00:22:34,223 --> 00:22:36,589
and what am I supposed
